# AI Platform Engine (APE)

## Architecture & Development Rules

> Product vision, scope, deployment model, domain model, and roadmap live in `project-context.mdc`.
> This document defines the engineering standards and architecture that implement that vision.

## Backend Rules

* Use async throughout the application (API, database, background tasks, and external providers where supported).
* Use SQLAlchemy ORM for database access; avoid raw SQL except for performance-critical or database-specific operations.
* Manage database sessions through centralized dependencies while keeping transaction boundaries explicit in services.
* Validate all request and response payloads using Pydantic schemas.
* Use enums instead of magic strings whenever values are predefined.
* Use standardized API response models and centralized response helpers for consistent success and error responses.
* Use centralized exception handlers for logging and client-safe error responses.
* Inject services into routers and repositories/providers into services using FastAPI dependency injection.
* Keep routers thin; business logic belongs in services.
* Keep services focused on orchestration and domain logic; infrastructure access belongs to repositories and providers.
* Keep repositories responsible only for relational database persistence.
* Keep provider implementations responsible only for external systems (LLMs, Vector DBs, Storage, OCR, APIs, etc.).
* Never expose vendor SDK models outside provider implementations.
* Return domain models or schemas from services; routers are responsible for HTTP response formatting.
* Use `response_model` consistently for OpenAPI documentation and response validation.
* Use `from_attributes=True` in response schemas that serialize ORM models.
* Centralize shared pagination, filtering, sorting, and query utilities instead of duplicating them across repositories.
* Use deterministic ordering for all list queries.
* Keep authentication and authorization centralized; routers should not perform authentication logic.
* Store shared constants, enums, and configuration in centralized modules. Avoid scattered magic values.
* Prefer configuration over hardcoded values wherever possible.
* Keep functions and classes small, focused, and easy to test.
* Favor composition over inheritance unless inheritance provides clear value.
* Minimize coupling between modules and maximize reusability.
* Write modular, testable, production-ready code following Clean Architecture principles.
* Long-running operations (OCR, parsing, embedding generation, indexing, evaluations, etc.) must execute asynchronously through background workers, never within synchronous HTTP requests.
* Add appropriate logging, tracing, and error handling for all infrastructure interactions.
* Write code that is provider-agnostic and supports future replacement of infrastructure components without changing business logic.

